==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Melt
<hw>Melt</hw> <pr>(m⟦ecr⟧lt)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Zool.)</fld>
<def>See 2d <er>Milt</er>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Melt</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Melt
<hw>Melt</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Melted</conjf> <mark>(obs.)</mark> <pos>p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Molten</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Melting</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[AS. <ets>meltan</ets>; akin to
Gr. <grk>me`ldein</grk>, E. <ets>malt</ets>, and prob. to E.
<ets>smelt</ets>, v. ⟦root⟧108. Cf. <er>Smelt</er>, <pos>v.</pos>,
<er>Malt</er>, <er>Milt</er> the spleen.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To
reduce from a solid to a liquid state, as by heat; to liquefy; <as>as,
to <ex>melt</ex> wax, tallow, or lead; to <ex>melt</ex> ice or
snow.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <specif>Hence:</specif> <def>To soften, as by a warming
or kindly influence; to relax; to render gentle or susceptible to mild
influences; sometimes, in a bad sense, to take away the firmness of; to
weaken.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Thou would'st have . . . <qex>melted</qex> down thy youth.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>For pity <qex>melts</qex> the mind to love.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- To liquefy; fuse; thaw; mollify;
soften.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Melt</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Melt
<hw>Melt</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To be changed from a
solid to a liquid state under the influence of heat; <as>as, butter and
wax <ex>melt</ex> at moderate temperatures</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To dissolve; <as>as, sugar <ex>melts</ex> in the
mouth</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <specif>Hence:</specif> <def>To be softened; to become
tender, mild, or gentle; also, to be weakened or subdued, as by
fear.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>My soul <qex>melteth</qex> for heaviness.</q> <rj><qau>Ps. cxix.
28.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Melting</qex> with tenderness and kind compassion.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To lose distinct form or outline; to blend. See
<er>fondue</er>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The soft, green, rounded hills, with their flowing outlines,
overlapping and <qex>melting</qex> into each other.</q> <rj><qau>J. C.
Shairp.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>To disappear by being dispersed or dissipated;
<as>as, the fog <ex>melts</ex> away</as>.</def>
<rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Meltable</ent>⟦br⟧
